[2] India (Punjab)
Date: Sun 12 Oct 2008
Source: MedIndia.com [edited]
<http://www.medindia.net/news/More-Than-650-Affected-by-Dengue-in-Ludhiana-42825-1.htm>


Over 650 confirmed cases of dengue fever and 2 dengue-related deaths
have been reported in Ludhiana.

A majority of the patients have been admitted to the city's Dayanand
Medical College for treatment against the illness, which is caused by
exposure to the [dengue virus transmitted by] the _Aedes aegypti_ mosquito.

Dengue is one of the oldest arthropod-borne diseases known in India.
Its characteristics include severe muscle and joint pains and fever
that can prove fatal in its severest form, i.e. dengue hemorrhagic fever (DHF).

"There are more than 300 cases from outside Ludhiana," said Satpal
Sharma, Ludhiana's Chief Medical Officer.

Patients and their relatives are facing a tough time combating the
disease, and they accuse the authorities of being ill equipped to
deal with the problem.

The World Health Organisation (WHO) says that factors like rapid
transportation, industrialization, movement of infected human
populations and mosquitoes and the changing ecology are responsible
for the spread of illnesses like dengue.

A senior official of the Ludhiana Municipal Corporation, S.P.
Ghumman, said: "Fogging (spraying of insecticide) is taking place
properly. The water accumulated in coolers is creating problem.
People are not maintaining proper sanitary conditions in their
houses. The water that accumulates in flower pots and coolers are
creating the problem. We have been saying this through media even. To
tackle this problem, we will start fining people."

Ludhiana saw a similar dengue fever outbreak in 1996, when 720 cases
and 19 deaths were reported.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Brent Barrett

[This report illustrates the common conflict concerning
responsibility for dengue virus mosquito vector control. The public
is blaming the government. Governmental public health officials blame
the public for not carrying out elimination of breeding sites of
_Aedes_, the dengue virus vectors, despite efforts to inform the
public. A few countries have resorted to inspection of houses and
other buildings with imposition of fines where _Aedes_ breeding sites
have been found.

An interactive map showing the location of Ludhiana in Punjab state
in India can be accessed at
<http://wwp.greenwichmeantime.com/time-zone/asia/india/ludhiana/map.htm>,
and a HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of India can be accessed
at <http://healthmap.org/promed?v=22.9,79.6,5>. - Mod.TY]

