[3] India (West Bengal)
Date: Sun 5 Oct 2008
From: The Statesman [edited]
<http://www.thestatesman.net/page.arcview.php?clid=22&id=252397&usrsess=1>


The city-based virus unit of the Indian Council of Medical Research
(ICMR) has sent a report to the state health department pointing out
that both dengue and chikungunya viruses have been circulating in
Bishnupur II block of South 24-Parganas.

According to the report, cases of dengue and chikungunya have been
confirmed in the same area. If chikungunya and dengue viruses
circulate in a particular area, there are chances of dual infection,
because both viruses are vectored by the same species of mosquito
_Aedes aegypti_. The last time this was witnessed was in 1962. At
that time, a number of people were killed owing to dual infection,
said a health department official.

Vector control measures are the only way to get a grip on the
situation. Last year [2007], these 2 diseases were detected in North
24-Parganas, but they were not circulating in a particular area,
another official added. Dengue and chikungunya experts say that if 2
different strains of dengue virus are in circulation in the state, it
could create a major threat.

The state health department had reportedly asked South 24-Parganas
authorities to carry out proper vector control measures.

--
Communicated by:
Dr Satadal Das, MD, DCP
Consultant Microbiologist
Peerless Hospital & BK Roy Research Centre
76 Satyen Roy Road
Kolkata 700034
