[6] Colombia
Date: Tue 2 Sep 2008
Source: Virology Journal 5 2008 [edited]
<http://www.pubmedcentral.nih.gov/articlerender.fcgi?tool=pubmed&pubmedid=18764951>


Dengue is a major health problem in tropical and subtropical regions.
In Colombia, dengue viruses (DENV) cause about 50 000 cases annually,
10 percent of which involve dengue hemorrhagic fever/dengue shock
syndrome. The picture is similar in other surrounding countries in
the Americas, with recent outbreaks of severe disease mostly
associated with DENV serotype 3 strains of the Indian genotype
introduced into the Americas in 1994.

The analysis of the 3'end (224 bp) of the envelope gene from 32
DENV-3 strains recently recovered in Colombia confirms the
circulation of the Indian genotype and, surprisingly, the
co-circulation of an Asian-Pacific genotype only recently described
in the Americas.

These results have important implications for epidemiology and
surveillance of DENV infection in Central and South America.
Molecular surveillance of the DENV genotypes infecting humans could
be a very valuable tool for controlling/mitigating the impact of the
DENV infection.

Reference:
Usme-Ciro JA, Mendez JA, Tenorio A, Rey GJ, Domingo C, Gallego-Gomez
JC. 2008. Simultaneous circulation of genotypes I and III of dengue
virus 3 in Colombia. Virol J. 5:101.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>

[It is important to track the movement of dengue virus serotypes and
genotypes and their relationship to the severity of disease.
Unfortunately, most of the information that comes to ProMED does not
mention the serotype of the dengue viruses involved in the reported
outbreaks, much less the genotypes. Dengue viruses and their _Aedes
aegypti_ vector have spread into the inter-Andean valleys in
Colombia, where they were not present 30 and more years ago. The
above article was cited by ProMED-ESP from the Spanish language 2 Sep
2008 issue of SciDevNet
<http://www.scidev.net/es/news/circula-en-colombia-nueva-cepa-de-virus-del-dengue.html>.

A map of Colombia can be accessed at
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/americas/colombia_pol_2001.jpg>. - Mod.TY]
